Can you run this in the Django shell on production? It will tell us exactly what's happening:


# Get a shell
docker exec -it allianceauth_gunicorn python manage.py shell
Then paste:


from aa_burnneweden.models import Contract
from allianceauth.eveonline.models import EveCharacter
from allianceauth.authentication.models import CharacterOwnership

fc = EveCharacter.objects.get(character_name="Flying Croissant")
print("character_id:", fc.character_id, "pk:", fc.pk)

co = CharacterOwnership.objects.filter(character=fc).first()
print("CharacterOwnership user:", co.user if co else "NONE — not linked!")

contracts = Contract.objects.filter(issuer_character=fc)
print("Total FC contracts:", contracts.count())
print("  issuer_user=NULL:", contracts.filter(issuer_user__isnull=True).count())
print("  issuer_user set:", contracts.filter(issuer_user__isnull=False).count())

for c in contracts[:5]:
    print(f"  contract {c.contract_id}: issuer_user={c.issuer_user_id} ({c.issuer_user})")
This will tell us one of three things:

CharacterOwnership user: NONE → the SSO add didn't create the ownership record properly
issuer_user=NULL on contracts → resolve_contract_issuers isn't running or is silently failing
issuer_user is set but to a different user → the contracts were created when Flying Croissant had a separate AA account
The fix path is different for each case.